"# Appendix D — Animating Emoji, Text, and Composed Motion

You can animate ANY text — words, emoji, hearts, faces, anything the terminal or the browser can show. This appendix teaches the whole ladder: from the one-line hello-world an eleven-year-old can type from memory, up to the composed physics-plus-easing-plus-fade stack a working animator builds when they need something to feel just right. Both are Motoi. Both are honest.

## The one-liner

Type this:

```scheme
(bounce \"🎉\")
```

That is it. The party popper hops off the ground, floats up a little, comes back down, and settles. You made your first animated glyph. No setup, no scene, no camera — just the verb and the thing.

Try more:

```scheme
(slide \"hi\" 'left)
(fade \"welcome\")
```

`slide` brings text in from an edge. `fade` grows opacity from invisible to visible. Three verbs, and you can already tell a small story with a smiley face and a greeting.

## Why it works

Under the hood, `bounce` is composed of two calls to `motion/move-to` — one going up with `easing/ease-in`, one coming down with `easing/ease-out`. The runtime paints the emoji with `fb/text` at each frame. You did not have to know any of that. You typed `(bounce \"🎉\")` and it worked. That is the entire deal.

But the moment you want more control, you get more control. `bounce` is a shortcut for a stack of parts, and every part is a verb you can compose yourself.

## The stack, one layer at a time

Here is the same bouncing emoji, written by hand:

```scheme
(define (my-bounce glyph x y height ms)
  (fb/text x y glyph)
  (motion/move-to glyph x (- y height) (quotient ms 2) :easing easing/ease-in)
  (motion/move-to glyph x y             (quotient ms 2) :easing easing/ease-out))

(my-bounce \"🎉\" 100 100 30 500)
```

Now you can change any layer. Want a bigger hop? Change `height`. Want it slower? Change `ms`. Want the settle to overshoot and spring back? Swap `easing/ease-out` for `easing/spring`.

## Cross-easing: three things happening at once

Real motion is rarely one axis. A cheerful hello-emoji should move UP, ROTATE a little, and FADE IN — all together, all with different easings. Motoi lets you compose:

```scheme
(define (hello-cheer glyph)
  (motion/move-to glyph (entity/x glyph) (- (entity/y glyph) 20)
                  400 :easing easing/emphasized)
  (entity/rotate! glyph 15 :duration 400 :easing easing/ease-in-out)
  (fade glyph :from 0.0 :to 1.0 :duration 400))

(hello-cheer \"👋\")
```

Three verbs, one gesture. The wave-hand emoji rises, tilts, and appears — all in 400ms. The three easings are different on purpose: the position uses `easing/emphasized` (strong deceleration, arrives with weight); the rotation uses `easing/ease-in-out` (a small comfortable turn); the opacity uses the default `easing/ease-in-out` inside `fade` (comes on smoothly). If you gave all three the same easing they'd feel mechanical. Different easings on different channels is what makes composed motion look alive.

## Text has size, and size is a choice

Emoji come in one size — the font paints them at whatever pixel dimensions the runtime supports. But TEXT has fonts and scales. The four font constants are your first design choice:

```scheme
(fb/text 20 10  \"MOTOI\" :font font/big)     ;; a title
(fb/text 20 30  \"hello\" :font font/default) ;; body
(fb/text 20 50  \"score\" :font font/mono)    ;; a HUD
(fb/text 20 70  \"fps 60\" :font font/tiny)   ;; a debug line
```

Bigger text carries more weight. Monospace communicates 'this is a number, and it will not wobble as digits change.' Tiny text says 'you don't need to look at this unless you're looking closely.' Choose by what you want the reader to feel, not by what looks the biggest.

## Measuring before drawing

Before you can center a title, you have to know how wide it is. `text/measure` is a pure function that gives you `(width height)` in pixels for a given string, font, and scale — without drawing anything:

```scheme
(define (center-title s cx y)
  (let* ((wh (text/measure s :font font/big))
         (w  (car wh)))
    (fb/text (- cx (quotient w 2)) y s :font font/big)))

(center-title \"WIN!\" 160 40)
```

You measured, then subtracted half the width from the center point, then drew. The title is centered no matter how long the string. This is a general shape — measure before you place — and it works for anything you want to position precisely.

## Long text: wrapping

If a string is longer than the space it can fit into, use `text/wrap` to break it into lines. Wrap is also pure — it plans the layout, doesn't draw:

```scheme
(define (paragraph x y width text)
  (let loop ((lines (text/wrap text width)) (dy 0))
    (cond ((null? lines) 'ok)
          (else (fb/text x (+ y dy) (car lines))
                (loop (cdr lines) (+ dy 10))))))

(paragraph 10 10 100 \"once upon a time a small fox found a bright red flower\")
```

Wrap gives you a list of lines. You draw them one by one, incrementing y for each. The result: a paragraph in a bounded column. Combine this with `fade` and you have a slowly-appearing text reveal — chapter opening, dialogue, story block.

## Composing multiple glyphs

The composition principle scales. Here is a small firework — three emoji, three bounces, three staggered starts:

```scheme
(define (firework x y)
  (fb/text x       y \"⭐\")
  (fb/text (+ x 20) y \"✨\")
  (fb/text (+ x 40) y \"⭐\")
  (bounce \"⭐\"  :height 30 :duration 500)
  (time/when 100 (lambda () (bounce \"✨\" :height 40 :duration 500)))
  (time/when 200 (lambda () (bounce \"⭐\" :height 30 :duration 500))))

(firework 100 200)
```

The three glyphs launch 100ms apart, each with its own bounce. Together they read as a cascade. This is orchestration — you pick when each part happens, and the sum is a scene.

## Chained easings

Sometimes one easing can't do the whole job. A card that flies in from the left, hovers a moment, and slides off to the right needs three easings in a row:

```scheme
(define (fly-through card)
  (motion/move-to card 40  100 300 :easing easing/decelerated)   ;; enter
  (time/when 300 (lambda ()
    (motion/move-to card 40  100 400 :easing easing/linear)))    ;; dwell
  (time/when 700 (lambda ()
    (motion/move-to card 320 100 300 :easing easing/accelerated)))) ;; exit

(fly-through 'notification)
```

Enter with `easing/decelerated` (arrives softly). Dwell with `easing/linear` (no drama; just sits). Exit with `easing/accelerated` (gathers speed and is gone). This is the enter/dwell/exit pattern, and it is the foundation of every UI that reads as *considered* rather than *thrown together*.

## Adult depth: custom bezier and spring

The named easings cover 90% of what you'll want. For the other 10%, build your own:

```scheme
;; A custom curve for a signature entrance
(define house-style (bezier-ease 0.05 0.7 0.1 1.0))

;; A physical spring tuned for a specific feel
(define playful (spring-ease :stiffness 220 :damping 8 :mass 1))
(define composed (spring-ease :stiffness 100 :damping 22 :mass 1))

(motion/move-to 'hero 200 100 500 :easing house-style)
(motion/move-to 'toy  100 100     :easing playful)
(motion/move-to 'card 200 100     :easing composed)
```

`bezier-ease` uses the same four-number convention as CSS `cubic-bezier()`. If a design spec says `cubic-bezier(0.05, 0.7, 0.1, 1.0)`, you type exactly that. `spring-ease` is physics: `stiffness` is how hard the spring pulls, `damping` is how quickly it settles, `mass` is inertia. Low damping = many bounces; high damping = one settle.

## When to reach for what

- One-line hello-world: `bounce`, `slide`, `fade`.
- Two things at once: two `motion/move-to` calls with different easings.
- A shape from a design spec: `bezier-ease` with the four numbers.
- Anything that should feel alive: `easing/spring` (or `spring-ease` for tuning).
- A clock hand or a progress bar: `easing/linear` — and only there.
- A hero title entering: `easing/emphasized`.
- Everything else, first choice: `easing/standard`.

## What this appendix does not do

It does not teach the physics of springs (that is in the Book of Motion, ch09-forces). It does not teach how the surface manages frames (that is ch01-surface). It does not teach the *why* of easing curves (ch03-easing in the Book of Motion goes deep on this). This appendix teaches: given the physics and the surface and the philosophy, HERE is how you paint text and emoji and compose motion in Motoi. The verbs are the point.

## A parting example

An eleven-year-old and a sixty-year-old are both writing a birthday card in Motoi. The eleven-year-old writes:

```scheme
(bounce \"🎂\")
(bounce \"🎉\")
(bounce \"❤️\")
```

Three bouncing emoji. The card works.

The sixty-year-old writes:

```scheme
(define (birthday-scene name)
  (let ((cake  \"🎂\") (party \"🎉\") (heart \"❤️\")
        (bg    (bezier-ease 0.1 0.0 0.3 1.0)))
    (slide  (string-append \"HAPPY BIRTHDAY \" name) 'top :duration 500)
    (time/when 400 (lambda () (bounce cake  :height 30 :duration 700)))
    (time/when 600 (lambda () (bounce party :height 40 :duration 700)))
    (time/when 800 (lambda () (bounce heart :height 25 :duration 900)))
    (time/when 1600 (lambda () (fade \"— from Motoi\" :from 0.0 :to 1.0 :duration 800)))))

(birthday-scene \"ALFRED\")
```

Same runtime. Same verbs. Different depth. The card that eleven-year-old wrote runs. The card the sixty-year-old wrote runs. Neither is more or less Motoi. That is what seamless means: the language does not force you to pick a floor.

